HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1035
By Salinas
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory and celebrate the life of
John Wilkins Haley of Memphis.
WHEREAS, it was with great sadness that the members of this General Assembly
learned of the untimely passing of John Wilkins Haley, who will be fondly remembered for his
sense of humor, artistic talent, humility, and compassion in action; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Haley was a world traveler who, through his diverse experiences in
early life, developed the courage to launch out into the world in service to others; and
WHEREAS, he had visited Holland, Germany, Spain, Mexico, South Sudan, Colombia,
England, and many more nations, and his fascination with other cultures and genuine interest in
people enabled him to connect easily wherever he went; and
WHEREAS, although he was a native of Memphis, John Haley lived in Hermosa Beach,
California, as a child before his family relocated to New Hampshire, where they resided in a
herdsman's trailer on a dairy farm for a time; and
WHEREAS, returning with his family to Memphis at the age of six, John Haley graduated
from White Station High School, attended Memphis College of Art, and earned a degree in
photography from Southern Illinois University; and
WHEREAS, after graduating from college, he worked as a photographer for The
Memphis Flyer and Memphis Magazine; he was also the photographer for Project Motion dance
collective, and this work ignited his passion for unexpected dramatic shots, often intentionally
taken out of focus; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Haley continued his interest in out-of-focus work with a series of flower
close ups taken with a simple Diana camera, his favorite work; and
HJR1035
013966
- 1 -

WHEREAS, while working as a photographer with the International Children's Heart
Foundation, John Haley traveled to war zones worldwide, documenting both the critical
surgeries and the living conditions of young patients and their families, often while experiencing
bombing and other war maneuvers; and
WHEREAS, while living in a FEMA trailer after Hurricane Katrina, John Haley worked on
community reconstruction in St. Bernard Parish, New Orleans, wisely reusing scrapped
materials for property restoration, a practice he would utilize again when rehabbing homes in
Memphis; and
WHEREAS, in 2005, Mr. Haley moved to Ireland, where he earned a master's degree in
peace and development studies from the University of Limerick; one of his projects there
involved election monitoring in Jerusalem during the 2006 legislative elections; and
WHEREAS, his work with non-governmental organizations next led him to Uganda,
where he met his future wife, Grace, winning her heart on their first date with a gesture that
captured the humility and generosity that defined him; and
WHEREAS, for five years, John Haley volunteered with the Butakoola Village
Association in Uganda’s Kayunga District, working to secure reliable access to clean drinking
water for a community long affected by illnesses caused by contamination; and
WHEREAS, he eventually identified an innovative building method using recycled plastic
bottles and mud, a demonstration of which led to the construction of a school bathroom and a
well that supplied safe, sanitary water to the community; word of this success spread across
Uganda and beyond, inspiring other communities throughout Africa; and
WHEREAS, in 2013, Mr. Haley returned to Memphis and was joined by Grace soon
thereafter; they would later marry and settle into the Binghampton community, where he applied
the techniques he learned in New Orleans to rehab affordable housing by using salvaged
- 2 - 013966

materials enhanced with bold color, thereby preserving each house's original design and
character; and
WHEREAS, at the time of Mr. Haley's death, he and Mrs. Haley were building Green
Dream Farm, an eco-retreat in Hoima, Uganda, which was named after the New Hampshire
farm where he had lived as a child; and
WHEREAS, John Haley's influence lives on in each life he touched; in his close
relationships with his nephews, he fostered a love of adventure, travel, and food; and
WHEREAS, John Wilkins Haley is survived by his wife, Grace Haley; his mother, Patricia
Haley (John Cooper); his father, Stephen Haley (Diana Bell); his stepdaughter, Sheila Karungi;
his brother, Jason Haley (Molly); his stepsister, Carole Cooper (Andrew) Moore and her sons,
Cooper and Forrest; his mother-in-law, Loy Rujumba; his aunt, Anne Porterfield (Wink); his
cousins, Lisa Bailey Evans (Jeff), Becky Van Wagoner (Christopher), and Lucas Wonert (Erica);
his nephews, Cullen Haley (Maria Berrios), Ethan Haley, Nathaniel Haley, and Joel Hochman;
and his niece, Sarah Hochman; and
WHEREAS, John Haley is mourned by a global community of friends and colleagues
and a large and loving family, and we wish to pay our respects to a gentleman who lived "life to
the lees" in devoted service to his fellow human beings; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we celebrate the life of John Wilkins Haley of Memphis, even as we honor
his memory and mourn his passing, remembering the purposeful life of a humble man who
accomplished much good in the world and was beloved by all who knew him.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we extend our condolences to Mr. Haley's family and
many friends.
- 3 - 013966

BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
